solution: ```class MyStack {
    private Queue<Integer> q1;
    private Queue<Integer> q2;

    public MyStack() {
        q1 = new LinkedList<>();
        q2 = new LinkedList<>();
    }

    public void push(int x) {
        q2.offer(x);
        while (!q1.isEmpty()) {
            q2.offer(q1.poll());
        }
        Queue<Integer> tmp = q1;
        q1 = q2;
        q2 = tmp;
    }

    public int pop() {
        return q1.poll();
    }

    public int top() {
        return q1.peek();
    }

    public boolean empty() {
        return q1.isEmpty();
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: push O(n), pop O(1), top O(1), empty O(1)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses two queues; always keeps the newest element at the front of q1 by reversing the order during push, making pop/top O(1).

